In late spring of 1975, tension between the colonists and the british officials finally erupted. The British had been deploying their famous âredcoatâ troops to the thirteen colonies; while the American militias had been gathering under cover. Began by what would be called âthe shot heard around the worldâ, the Battle of Lexington and Concord ignited the age-defining American Revolutionary War. The war can be divided into three main stages, the initial battles, hardship before the Battle of Saratoga, and the final stages of the war. 
    Due to events like the Boston Massacre, the Intolerable Acts, and various other British infringements on the rights of the American colonists, the relationship between King George III and his subjects in the  new world wasnât very cordial. Militias dubbed as the âminutemenâ(as they could be ready to fight in a minute) were being rallied all across the thirteen colonies. Formal war broke out when the British tried to seize the weapons that the Patriots stocked in Concord. After the strategic victory of the Americans at Lexington and Concord, the Continental Army, led by General George Washington, was formally founded. On July 4 of 1776, the independence of America was declared. Despite all these, the revolutionary army was constantly defeated by better-equipped British soldiers and were forced to retreat behind the Delaware River. 
    When the Americas were lacking the morale to keep fighting against the strongest empire in the world then, Washington inspired the Continental Army to an important victory in Trenton, NJ. Even with the victory depicted by the famous painting of Washington sailing across the Delaware River, the situation didnât get any easier for the Patriots. The British had a plan to separate New England, the most developed part of the thirteen colonies from the others. To achieve this, General Burgoyne directed his army southward in order to link with other British troops stationed at New York. Due to unwise deployment strategies of the British, Burgoyneâs army was left vulnerable near Saratoga, NY. General Horatio Gates took advantage of the situation and crushed the British army there. This battle would be called the Battle of Saratoga, often considered as the turning point of the Revolutionary War. After the Battle of Saratoga, the French formally joined the war, as the revolutionaires proved that they were capable of winning. 
    Thanks to the formal declaration of war of France, Prussian officers and French generals, including Marquis de  Lafayette, arrived to assist the Continental Army. After some fighting in the South and naval battles between the French and British, the Continental Army seized an opportunity to encircle British troops in the Yorktown Peninsula in Virginia. General Cornwallis, the British leader of the encircled army. Unable to resist the artillery barrage of the Americans and the naval blockade of the French, General Cornwallis surrendered to Washington on October 19, 1981. Although some historians consider the Battle of Yorktown as the end of the Revolutionary War, the British still had a considerable presence in the Americas until the signature of the Treaty of Paris, which formally recognized the independence of the thirteen colonies.

July 4th, 1776, is the independence day of the United States of America. The journey of pursuing this day of liberty and independence that people now celebrate was not easy. The American colonies had come a long way to declaring independence. The American Revolution played a huge part of this process. The revolution took place because of the interminable tension between the colonists and the British, and because of the new ideas emerged then. 
Since Britain mostly turned to the American colonies for resources and money as debts from the French and Indian War, the tension between the colonists and Britain rose quickly. First, parliament passed the Stamp Act, which required colonists to purchase stamped paper for every kind of legal document. People who disobeyed would be convicted. Because of this act, a secret group called Sons of Liberty, led by Samuel Adams, used extreme tactics to stop the stamps from being sold. Also, the colonial assemblies protested that without their representatives, they could not be taxed by Parliament. This was the first time that the separated colonies acted as one. Later on, other people and women, calling themselves the Daughters of Liberty,  joined the protest by boycotting British-manifactured goods until the act was repealed. After the Stamp Act was repealed, a new Townshend Act was imposed. It levied duties on imported materials such as glass, pain, and paper that came from Britain. The colonists protested âtaxation without representationâ and call ed for another boycott. The British sent troops to Boston which intensified the conflict and led to the Boston Massacre. 
The next immediate tension was caused by the Boston Massacre, the Boston Tea Party, and the reaction of the King. A fight between the colonists and the British soldiers came to be known as the Boston Massacre. Five men were killed, and the conflict was depicted as a massacre by agitators in order to unite the colonists. The assemblies of Massachusetts and Virginia set up committees of correspondence to communicate with other colonies about this and other threats to American liberties, further linking the leaders like what a government does. In 1773, The British East India Company, which held an official monopoly on tea imports, had been hit hard by boycotts. Therefore, Parliament passed the Tea Act, which allowed only the company to sell tea without tax, to save the bankrupt company. Boston's rebels disguised themselves as Native Americans and dumped 18000 pounds of tea into the waters of Boston Harbor. This was later known as the Boston Tea Party. The king was furious, so he made Parliament pass the Intolerable Acts which closed Boston Harbor and Quartering Act which authorized commanders to house soldiers in private buildings. In response to the punishment, the committees of correspondence assembled the First Continental Congress. In the congress, the delegates drew up a declaration of colonial rights, including running their own affairs, and agreed that they would fight back if the British used violence.
Because the tension rose, colonists began storing weapons, and the action sparked the first armed battle prior to the revolution. General Gage was told by an agent that the colonistsâ arms were stored in barns, empty buildings, and private homes. He gathered troops and marched to Concord, Massachusetts to seize the weapons. The minutemen, also known as civilian soldiers, intercepted the British and engaged in the first battle. The battle was famous for the âshot heard around the world.â
Besides action taken by the British government and colonists, ideas also triggered the American Revolution. By the Second Continental Congress, still many colonists believed in peaceful resolution. They drafted the Olive Branch Petition which called for return to âformer harmony.â However, King Geroge III rejected and even ordered a naval blockade of the American coast. Then, Common Sense by Thomas Paine sparked the idea of gaining independence. He argued that it was Americaâs âdestinyâ to be independent from British enemies. This work helped overcome the doubts about separating from Britain. Furthermore, when Thomas Jefferson drafted the Declaration of Independence, he considered John Lockeâs ideas. He drew on the ânatural rightsâ to life, liberty, and property, and gave people the right to abolish government that threatened their âunalienable rights.â The piece stated that âall men are created equal,â but the British King violated the rights; therefore, he was to be overthrown; patriots eventually declared Independence. 
The American Revolution happened because of a series of tension and conflicts between the colonists and Britain. First, several taxation acts were passed which led to peopleâs resentment and plans to rebel. Also, ideas of gaining independence flourished by the publication of famous works of Paine and Jefferson. Not just one incident but all that led to the American Revolution.
